items.name: Object_Visual
items.content: # =================================================================== # # Script: Object_Visual # # $$COPYRIGHT$$ # # =================================================================== class Object_Visual extends gs.Object_Base ###* * The base class for all regular visual game objects. * * @module * @class Object_Visual * @extends gs.Object_Base * @memberof vn * @constructor ### constructor: (data) -> super() ###* * Indiciates if the game object is visible on screen. * @property visible * @type boolean ### @visible = yes ###* * The object's destination rectangle on screen. * @property dstRect * @type gs.Rect ### @dstRect = new Rect(data?.x, data?.y) ###* * The object's origin. * @property origin * @type gs.Point ### @origin = new gs.Point(0, 0) ###* * The object's offset. * @property offset * @type gs.Point ### @offset = new gs.Point(0, 0) ###* * The object's anchor-point. For example: An anchor-point with 0,0 places the object with its top-left corner * at its position but with an 0.5, 0.5 anchor-point the object is placed with its center. An anchor-point of 1,1 * places the object with its lower-right corner. * @property anchor * @type gs.Point ### @anchor = new gs.Point(0.0, 0.0) ###* * The position anchor point. For example: An anchor-point with 0,0 places the object with its top-left corner * at its position but with an 0.5, 0.5 anchor-point the object will be placed with its center. An anchor-point of 1,1 * will place the object with its lower-right corner. It has not effect on the object's rotation/zoom anchor. For that, take * a look at anchor property. * * @property positionAnchor * @type gs.Point ### @positionAnchor = new gs.Point(0, 0) ###* * The object's zoom-setting for x and y axis. The default value is * { x: 1.0, y: 1.0 } * @property zoom * @type gs.Point ### @zoom = data?.zoom || new gs.Point(1.0, 1.0) ###* * The object's z-index controls rendering-order/image-overlapping. An object with a smaller z-index is rendered * before an object with a larger index. For example: To make sure a game object is always on top of the screen, it * should have the largest z-index of all game objects. * @property zIndex * @type number ### @zIndex = 700 ###* * The object's blend mode controls how the blending of the object's visual representation is calculated. * @property blendMode * @type number * @default gs.BlendMode.NORMAL ### @blendMode = gs.BlendMode.NORMAL ###* * The object's viewport. * @property viewport * @type gs.Viewport ### @viewport = Graphics.viewport ###* * The object's motion-blur settings. * @property motionBlur * @type gs.MotionBlur ### @motionBlur = new gs.MotionBlur() ###* * Contains different kinds of shader effects which can be activated for the object. * @property effects * @type gs.EffectCollection ### @effects = new gs.EffectCollection() ###* * The object's opacity to control transparency. For example: 0 = Transparent, 255 = Opaque, 128 = Semi-Transparent. * @property opacity * @type number ### @opacity = 255 ###* * Restores the game object from a data-bundle. * * @method restore * @param {Object} data - The data-bundle. ### restore: (data) -> if data.components @componentsFromDataBundle(data) Object.mixin(this, data) @dstRect = gs.Rect.fromObject(data.dstRect) @motionBlur = gs.MotionBlur.fromObject(data.motionBlur) gs.Object_Visual = Object_Visual
